Why America must not re-elect President Bush
I have never been particularly politically engaged, but these are not normal times.
President George W. Bush endangers the security of the United States and the world and at the same time undermines American values.
Due to my opposition to him, I was demonized by Bush's campaign team.
President Bush entered the 2000 election with a platform promising an "humility" foreign policy.
Falls er wiedergewählt wird, so ist dies ein Votum für die Bush-Doktrin des Präventivkrieges - und den Einmarsch im Irak -, und die Welt wird mit den Folgen leben müssen.
Indem es Bushs Politik an den Wahlurnen zurückweist, hat Amerika eine Chance, den Respekt und die Unterstützung der Welt zurückzuerlangen.
Die Terroranschläge vom 11. September 2001 erforderten eine starke Antwort.
Sie haben jedoch auch dazu geführt, dass der für die Demokratie so unverzichtbare kritische Prozess - die umfassende und redliche Diskussion der anstehenden Probleme - außer Kraft gesetzt wurde.
Bush hat die Kritik zu Schweigen gebracht, indem er sie für unpatriotisch erklärte.
Für die Dauer von 18 Monaten im Anschluss an den 11. September hat er es geschafft, jeglichen Dissens zu unterdrücken.
Auf diese Weise hat er Amerika in die falsche Richtung geführt.
Tatsächlich hat Bush Osama bin Laden direkt in die Hände gespielt.
Der Einmarsch in Afghanistan - wo bin Laden lebte und die Al Kaida ihre Trainingslager unterhielt - war gerechtfertigt.
Der Einmarsch im Irak war es nicht.
He was Bush's unintended gift to bin Laden.
Immediately following 9/11, there were spontaneous expressions of sympathy for America all around the world.
These have given way to widespread resentment.
Significantly more people today are willing to risk their lives to kill Americans than on 9/11.
Bush likes to claim that the terrorists hate what Americans are - a freedom-loving people - not what they do.
Krieg und Besatzung jedoch bringen unschuldige Opfer hervor.
Wir Amerikaner zählen unsere gefallenen Soldaten - mehr als 1.000 im Irak.
Die übrige Welt zählt auch die jeden Tag getöteten Iraker - vielleicht zwanzig Mal so viele.
Ebenso wenig war die Folter von Insassen im Gefängnis von Abu Ghraib das Werk einiger weniger „fauler Äpfel".
Sie war Teil eines von Verteidigungsminister Donald Rumsfeld eingerichteten Systems für den Umgang mit Gefangenen.
The world is condemning America, and our troops in Iraq are paying the price for it.
Bush has convinced people that America's safety is in good hands with him, by addressing the fears caused by the attacks of September 11.
When danger looms, people rally around their flag, and Bush exploited this by fostering a sense of threat.
His campaign assumes that people ultimately don't care about the truth and will almost believe anything if repeated often enough.
There must be something wrong with America if we fall for it.
For example, still about 40% of all Americans believe that Saddam Hussein had something to do with 9/11, even though the 9/11 Commission - appointed by Bush and chaired by a Republican - clearly determined that no such connection existed.
One would like to scream: "Wake up, America.
Do you not realize that you are being led by the nose?"
The war in Iraq was based on false premises from start to finish - if it ends at all.
It was a war decided upon of its own accord, not out of necessity.
Much more, America went to war under a pretext: mass destruction weapons could not be found, and the connection to Al Qaeda could not be proven.
Bush then claimed that America went to war to free Iraq.
But one cannot impose democracy by force.
Saddam Hussein was a tyrant, and the Iraqi people—and the world—can be glad to be rid of him.
But America had the duty to ensure justice and order; instead, we watched idly as Baghdad and other cities were looted.
Had we really cared about the Iraqi people, we would have had to provide a much larger number of soldiers for occupation.
We would not only have had to protect the Ministry of Oil, but also other ministries, museums, and hospitals.
Worse yet: Where American soldiers encountered resistance, they applied methods - such as entering private homes and mistreating prisoners - that shocked and humiliated the population, causing anger and resentment.
The retreats and blunders of the Bush administration are legion.
First, the Iraqi army was disbanded, then America tried to rebuild it.
First, the USA tried to eliminate the Baathists, then America sought their help.
When the uprisings could no longer be controlled, America installed an Iraqi government.
The man chosen as its leader was a CIA protégé with the reputation of a "strongman" - hardly a democratic decision.
Despite the efforts of Bush's campaign team to paint a rosy picture, the situation in Iraq is bleak.
A large part of the western province has been left to the insurgents. The prospects for the free and fair elections scheduled for January are rapidly diminishing.
Bürgerkrieg droht.
Bush's war in Iraq has also inflicted immense damage on America, weakened its military might, and undermined the morale of the troops.
Before the war, America projected an impression of overwhelming strength.
No longer.
Afghanistan is slipping out of control.
North Korea, Iran, Pakistan, and other countries are pursuing nuclear programs with renewed energy.
One can criticize the Bush Administration on many other political issues, but none of them is as significant as Iraq.
The costs of the war have so far amounted to nearly 200 billion dollars and will rise further, because the invasion of Iraq was much easier than the withdrawal will be.
Bush taunted John Kerry, asking him to explain what he would have done differently.
Kerry responded that he would have done everything differently and that he would have been in a better position to extricate us from our entanglement.
But this will not come easily to him either, for America is mired in a quagmire.
Leading military experts and diplomats warned Bush vehemently not to invade Iraq.
He ignored them.
He suppressed the critical process with the argument that any criticism of the commander-in-chief endangered the U.S. troops.
But this is Bush’s war, and he should be held accountable for it.
Die Amerikaner sollten einen Augenblick innehalten und sich die Frage stellen: Wem haben wir diesen Schlamassel zu verdanken?
Ein Augenblick des Nachdenkens dürfte eine weitere Frage aufwerfen: Qualifiziert Bushs Cowboy-Gehabe ihn, Amerikas Oberbefehlshaber zu bleiben?
